Song Lyrics Data Story
¶

A deeper look of patterns and characteristics of different types of song lyrics
¶

In [125]:
from IPython.display import Image
Image(filename='music3.jpg', width = 700)
Out[125]:

We all love music and singers, and we may have our favorite playlist that we listen to every day. With the continuous development of technology, we have the opportunity to explore different types of music more and easier. Some of us like Pop music, some like country music, and some enjoy EDM more. Music is everywhere and has become an indispensable part of our life. People love different songs due to different reasons. We can fall in love with a song because of its melody, or sometimes we feel like the lyrics resonate with us so well. It's very interesting to study people's music preferences and the reason behind. Let's take a look at the secret of songs -- the lyrics! And find out the patterns of different types of song lyrics!

What type of songs do we have?¶

First, we will take a look at some basic information so that we can get a better understanding of the songs we have. In this part, the song distribution among music genre, artist and year of release will be analyzed.

Does percentage of punctuation in lyrics matter?¶

The violin plot shows that most songs have around 0-5% punctuation in lyrics.

In [26]:
# create feature for % lyrics that is punctuation

import string

def punct_count(lyrics):
    count = sum([1 for char in lyrics if char in string.punctuation])
    return round(count/(len(lyrics) - lyrics.count(' ')),3)*100

data['punct_perc'] = data['lyrics'].apply(lambda x: punct_count(x))

Word Count¶

After getting some basic information of songs and lyrics, we can take a closer look at the actual text in lyrics. Most importantly, we want to understand if certain words are commonly used in certain type of songs, and are there special sentiments or topics tied to any genre.

First, let's take a look at the song with longest lyrics and see the frequency of words in the song¶

From previous analysis, we found that song 'yes-sir-i-will' has the longest lyrics. Let's check the most common words in this song!

In [32]:
subset = data[data['song'] == 'yes-sir-i-will']
In [33]:
from collections import Counter

word_freq = Counter(word for words in subset['stemmedwords'].str.split() for word in words)
print('Top 10 most common words in the song are:', word_freq.most_common(10))

Top 10 most common words in the song are: [('people', 36), ('world', 24), ('passive', 18), ('war', 18), ('care', 17), ('death', 15), ('suffer', 15), ('power', 13), ('accept', 13), ('thatcher', 13)]

Summary¶

By utilizing topic modeling techinique, we grouped the words in lyrics into 8 topis and below shows 10 keywords under each topics.

In [37]:
#Apply TFIDF Vecterizer

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer

tfidf_vect = TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english', min_df=10, max_df=0.9)
X_tfidf = tfidf_vect.fit_transform(data['stemmedwords']) # fit vectors of unique word counts in stemmed words
#print('TFIDF matrix dimensions:',X_tfidf.shape)
#print(tfidf_vect.get_feature_names())
In [38]:
# Latent Dirichlet Allocation(LDA)

from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation as LDA

k_topics = 8
lda = LDA(n_components=k_topics, max_iter=10, learning_method='online', random_state=1234)
lda.fit(X_tfidf)
Out[38]:

             evaluate_every=-1, learning_decay=0.7,
             learning_method='online', learning_offset=10.0,
             max_doc_update_iter=100, max_iter=10, mean_change_tol=0.001,
             n_components=8, n_jobs=None, n_topics=None, perp_tol=0.1,
             random_state=1234, topic_word_prior=None,
             total_samples=1000000.0, verbose=0)
In [39]:
tfidf_features = tfidf_vect.get_feature_names()
top_n_words = 10
word_dict = dict()

for i in range(0,k_topics):
    topic = pd.DataFrame(data={'word':tfidf_features, 'weight':lda.components_[i]})
    sorted_topic = topic.sort_values('weight', ascending=False).head(top_n_words)
    word_dict[i+1] = list(sorted_topic['word'])

pd.DataFrame(word_dict)

Based the above LDA result, here are the interpretations of each topic:

Topic 1: technology/universe/outer space
Topic 2: hapiness/love
Topic 3: dark(sensitive words)
Topic 4: obstacles/challenges
Topic 5: life purpose/goal
Topic 6: sorrow
Topic 7: lifestyle/countryside
Topic 8: travel/life

We also notice that some of the keywords are overlapped with others under different topics, which indicates that their topics are similar and we may try to reduce the number of topics in further analysis to improve accuracy of result.

Wordcloud¶

Below is the word cloud showing most frequent words that appear in all songs.

In [52]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)

def show_wordcloud(data):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='lightgrey',
        stopwords=stopwords,
        max_words=150,
        max_font_size=55, 
        scale=4,
    ).generate(str(data))

    fig = plt.figure(1, figsize=(12, 12))
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.show()

show_wordcloud(data['stemmedwords'])

After looking at the wordcloud for each genre, we can assign topics to each genre based on the keywords and sentiments:

Topic 4: obstacles/challenges --> Pop
Topic 2: hapiness/love and Topic 7: lifestyle --> Country
Topic 5: life purpose/goal --> Rock
Topic 3: dark --> Hip-Pop
Topic 6: sorrow --> Metal

It is very interesting that although different genres share a lot of common words such as love, youre, ive, time, bab, etc., they do have significanly emotions, and they differ in lyrics length too.
